    <div id="main_content_wrap" class="outer">
      <section id="main_content" class="inner">
        <p>This is a weekly series of informal talks given by people enthusiastic about Theoretical Computer Science. The goal is to have an interactive session discussing papers, book chapters or anything worthwhile that would broaden our common knowledge. The speaker should consider the background of the audience and spend ample time in laying the basics of the material before going on to the nitty-gritties. Also note this is <em>not</em> a platform to prove one's smartness but mutually learn something new.</p>

<br/>
<p>
<iframe src="https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?showTitle=0&amp;showPrint=0&amp;showTz=0&amp;height=300&amp;wkst=2&amp;bgcolor=%23ffffff&amp;src=10ncrbr8s8knk7bq58qar449lk%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;color=%23711616&amp;ctz=Asia%2FCalcutta" style=" border-width:0 " width="500" height="300" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe>
</p>
<br/>

<hr>
<h2>
<a id="week-3" class="anchor" href="#week-3" aria-hidden="true"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>March 30, 2015</h2>
<p><strong>On the Convergence of the Hegselmann-Krause System<br/> </strong>
Speaker: Kirankumar Shiragur </p>
<ul>
Here are the references:
<li>
$O(n^3)$ in 1-dimension, $O(n^{10} d^2)$ in $d$-dimension and $O(n^2 )$ lower bound in 2-dimension is from this <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1211.1909">paper</a>.
</li>
<li>
$O(n^3)$ independent result using lyapunov function for 1-dimension <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1211.4189">[link]</a>.
</li>
<li>
$O(n^4)$ in any dimension(independent of dimension) <a href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1501.02183.pdf">[link]</a>.
</li>
<li>
Equidistant configuration is very well studied in this <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1406.0819">paper</a>.
</li>
<li>
Lower bound of $O(n^2)$ is 1-dimension(Dumbbell configuration) <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1406.0769">[link]</a>.
</li>
<li>
Strategic agents model is novel and studied in this <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1411.4814">paper</a>.
</li>
<li>
Here are our results on social HK model and non-determinsitic HK model <a href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1503.01720.pdf">[link]</a>.
</li>
<li>
There is recent convergence result on a special case of Heterogenous case, where the agents can have a confidence bound of either 0 or 1, for more details you can go through this <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1502.03332">paper</a>.
</li>
<li>
These are the two remarkable papers from Bernard Chazelle in this area, where he proves convergence and periodicity and other crazy stuffs for much general graphs. See <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1204.3946">here</a> and
<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1004.1447">here</a> again.
</li>
<li>
 Lastly I thought to cover another technique used in proving convergence in this area called the Adjoining dynamics. I am attaching a brief highlighted <a href="hk/Adjoining Dynamics.pdf">points</a> about this technique. However if you find it interesting and want to read more about it you can read these other attached papers <a href="hk/06190199.pdf">here</a> and <a href="hk/06580008.pdf">there</a>.
</li>
</ul>

<h2>
<a id="week-2" class="anchor" href="#week-2" aria-hidden="true"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>March 23, 2015</h2>
<p><strong>The Lovasz Local Lemma<br/> </strong>
Speaker: Ninad Rajgopal </p>
<ul>
<li>
The best reference for the probabilistic method -
<a href="http://nguyen.hong.hai.free.fr/EBOOKS/SCIENCE%20AND%20ENGINEERING/MATHEMATIQUE/PROBABILITY/The_Probabilistic_Method.pdf">The Probabilistic Method (Alon and Spencer) </a> </li>
Chapter 5 talks about Lovasz Local Lemma and it's applications.
<li>
Another nice reference is this set of lecture notes by Matousek and Vondrak.
<a href="https://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs.cmu.edu/academic/class/15859-f09/www/handouts/matousek-vondrak-prob-ln.pdf">The Probabilistic Method (Matousek and Vondrak) </a> </li>
</li>
<li>
I could not cover the algorithmic aspects of the LLL. There have been many papers which have looked at the constructive (algorithmic) versions of this technique,
with the most famous one being the <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/0903.0544"> paper </a> by Moser and Tardos, which gives a constructive proof for the LLL. Hopefully, I might be able to 
bring it up on a later date.
</li>
</ul>

<h2>
<a id="week-1" class="anchor" href="#week-1" aria-hidden="true"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>March 2, 2015</h2>

<p><strong>Constructive Discrepancy Minimization by Walking on The Edges.<br/> </strong> <em> Shachar Lovett and Raghu Meka.</em> FOCS 2012 <br/>
Speaker: Aniket Basu Roy </p>


<ul>
<li>
<a href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1203.5747.pdf">Link to the paper (arXiv) </a> </li>
<li>
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dwCfsKpc2gU">Tutorial video (a rather long one)</a> </li>
<li>
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=60bnvzm5YY0">tcs+ video where the first half discusses the result</a><br>
</li>
</ul>

<p>The technique of randomly walking in polytopes have been used for developing approximation algorithms as well. The following 2 papers are relevant.
  We might look at them in the future. </p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1301.4010">Thomas Rothvoss. <em>Approximating Bin Packing within O(log OPT * log log OPT) bins</em> FOCS 2013</a></li>
<li>
<a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/%7Eravishan/bcast-14.pdf">Nikhil Bansal, Moses Charikar, Ravishankar Krishnaswamy and Shi Li.
<em>Better Algorithms and Hardness for Broadcast Scheduling via a Discrepancy Approach</em> SODA 2014</a><br>
</li>
</ul>

<p>To know more about Discrepancy Theory in general, the following 2 books are available.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.cs.princeton.edu/%7Echazelle/pubs/book.pdf">Bernard Chazelle. The Discrepancy Method</a></li>
<li><a href="http://kam.mff.cuni.cz/%7Ematousek/di.html">Jiri Matousek. Geometric Discrepancy</a></li>
</ul>

      </section>
